Secured and monitored three-server web infrastructure for `www.foobar.com`:

- Domain: `foobar.com`
- DNS:
  - `www` is a `CNAME` record pointing to `foobar.com`
  - `foobar.com` is an `A` record pointing to the load balancer public IP
- Server 1:
  - `HAproxy` (load balancer)
  - Firewall
  - SSL certificate for `www.foobar.com` (HTTPS termination)
  - Monitoring client/agent
- Server 2:
  - `Nginx` (web server)
  - Application server
  - Application files (code base)
  - `MySQL` Primary
  - Firewall
  - Monitoring client/agent
- Server 3:
  - `Nginx` (web server)
  - Application server
  - Application files (code base)
  - `MySQL` Replica
  - Firewall
  - Monitoring client/agent

Why each additional element is added:
- 3 Firewalls: Restrict inbound and outbound traffic per server and reduce attack surface.
- SSL certificate: Encrypts traffic between clients and infrastructure for confidentiality and integrity.
- 3 Monitoring clients: Collect metrics/logs/events from each server and send them to a central monitoring platform.

What firewalls are for:
- Enforcing network access rules (allowed ports/protocols/IP ranges).
- Blocking unauthorized connections between internet, load balancer, app tier, and database tier.

Why traffic is served over HTTPS:
- Encrypts data in transit to prevent sniffing and man-in-the-middle attacks.
- Verifies server identity with certificates.
- Required for secure authentication, sessions, and modern browser trust.

What monitoring is used for:
- Detecting outages, high latency, resource saturation, and abnormal behavior.
- Triggering alerts so incidents are handled quickly.
- Supporting troubleshooting and capacity planning.

How the monitoring tool collects data:
- Agent-based collection: each monitoring client reads system/application metrics and logs locally.
- The agent periodically pushes telemetry to the monitoring backend (for example, Sumologic).

How to monitor web server QPS:
- Enable request metrics on `Nginx` (for example via access logs, status module, or exporter).
- Configure the monitoring agent to scrape/collect request count.
- Build a dashboard/query calculating QPS (requests per second).
- Set alerts on QPS anomalies (unexpected spikes or drops).

Request flow:
1. User requests `https://www.foobar.com`.
2. DNS resolves to the load balancer IP.
3. Client establishes TLS session with `HAproxy` using the SSL certificate.
4. `HAproxy` forwards traffic to backend web/app servers.
5. Application processes logic and accesses database (writes to Primary, reads can use Replica).
6. Monitoring agents on all three servers continuously report health/metrics/logs.

Issues with this infrastructure:
- SSL termination at load balancer:
  - Traffic from load balancer to backend may be unencrypted if not re-encrypted internally.
  - Internal network compromise could expose sensitive data.
- Only one MySQL write node:
  - Primary is a write bottleneck and a write SPOF.
  - Primary failure can stop write operations until failover/promotion is completed.
- Same components on all servers:
  - Mixed roles increase operational complexity and resource contention.
  - Harder isolation, scaling, and security policy management between web/app/database layers.https://imgur.com/your-task2-screenshot-link

